shit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Malcolm","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of the medieval Gaelic name <i>Mael Coluim</i> ‘devotee of St Columba’. Columba was a 6th-century monk of Irish origin who played a leading part in the conversion to Christianity of Scotland and northern England;  see also  Callum   and   Colm .  He has always been one of the most popular saints in Scotland, but in the Middle Ages it was felt to be presumptuous to give the names of saints directly to children; instead their blessing was invoked by prefixing the name with <i>mael</i> ‘devotee of’ or <i>gille</i> ‘servant of’. Since the 1930s the given name has been used widely in the English-speaking world, not just by those with Scottish connections."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Malcolm de Dalrympil was born about 1293, in Dalrymple, Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Gilchrist de Dalrympil, Baron Dalrymple, was 31 and his mother, Mrs Gilchrist de Dalrympil, was 25. He married Mrs Malccolm Dalrympil. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"about 1293–":"umbes 1293–Surnud","1293–Male":"1293–Surnud","1298–Female":"1298–Surnud","1370–Male":"1370–Surnud","1339–Male":"1339–Surnud","1342–Male":"1342–Surnud","1264–Male":"1264–Surnud","1269–Female":"1269–Surnud","about 1293":"umbes 1293","1269":"1269","about 1339":"umbes 1339","Abt 1342":"umbes 1342","1342":"1342","1298":"1298","1264":"1264","1370":"1370","1293":"1293","1339":"1339","Dalrymple, Ayr, Scotland":"Dalrymple, Ayrshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1293–":"noin 1293–Kuollut","1293–Male":"1293–Ku